From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] amdgpu: v45 - dce_v8_0 manual PLL programming for Liverpool 1080p60

Builds on top of v44 (0019). v44's diagnostic dump confirmed all four
DCCG_PLL[0..3] register banks are at zero when dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set
runs — PS4 firmware's display PLL state does NOT survive the kexec from
PS4-OS into Linux. amdgpu has to program the display PLL itself, and
ATOM AdjustDisplayPll/SetPixelClock can't help (PS4 VBIOS table data is
stub).

This patch replaces v44's "preserve BIOS state" short-circuit with a
direct PPLL register programmer.

Target mode: 1080p60 = 148.5 MHz pixel clock.
Reference clock: 100 MHz (PCIE refclk on CIK).
Standard avivo PLL math:
  pixel_clock = ref_clock * (fb_div_int + fb_div_frac/16) / ref_div / post_div
For 148.5 MHz with our chosen dividers:
  ref_div = 1, fb_div_int = 11, fb_div_frac = 14, post_div = 8
  → 100 * (11 + 14/16) / 1 / 8 = 148.4375 MHz (within HDMI ±0.5% tolerance)
  → VCO = 100 * 11.875 = 1187.5 MHz (within typical 600..1600 MHz range)

Register layout from dce_8_0_sh_mask.h VGA*_PPLL_* defines (DCCG_PLL
banks share the layout — both are CIK PPLL register banks, just routed
for different consumers):
  PLL_REF_DIV [9:0]    = ref_div
  PLL_FB_DIV  [3:0]    = fb_div_frac (4-bit fractional)
  PLL_FB_DIV  [26:16]  = fb_div_int  (11-bit integer)
  PLL_POST_DIV[6:0]    = post_div_pixclk (7-bit)

Programs ALL four PPLLs with identical dividers. Whichever PPLL the
PIXCLK_RESYNC routes to our CRTC will then have valid dividers driving
its clock output. Overkill (other PPLLs aren't driving any active
output) but safe.

Dumps PRE and POST register state for diagnostic. PLL_CNTL also dumped
to see what enable/sleep state the PLL is in (might be powered down,
which dividers alone won't fix).

Three possible outcomes:
  A) Display lights up — confirmed root cause was unprogrammed PLL.
     Future v46 will replicate this for arbitrary modes (compute
     dividers from adjusted_mode->clock instead of hardcoding 1080p60).
  B) Display still dark, PPLL POST-program reads back the values we
     wrote — register layout is right, PLL is taking the dividers,
     but it's powered down or upstream chain (DP TX, DIG encoder)
     still doesn't have signal. v46 will add PLL_CNTL enable
     sequencing.
  C) PPLL POST-program reads back differently than what we wrote —
     register layout assumption is wrong, dividers stuck. v46 will
     consult radeon's CIK PLL helper as reference.

NOT doing in this iteration: PLL enable/reset/lock sequencing via
PLL_CNTL/PLL_UPDATE_LOCK. Mode generalization (only 1080p60 hardcoded
right now). PIXCLK_RESYNC routing setup (we trust whatever BIOS or
amdgpu init left). DP TX or DIG encoder programming.

---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/dce_v8_0.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/dce_v8_0.c
@@ -2569,42 +2569,109 @@
 		amdgpu_crtc->adjusted_clock = adjusted_mode->clock;
 	}

-	/* v44 (PS4 Liverpool/Gladius): PS4 VBIOS lacks usable ATOM AdjustDisplayPll/
-	 * SetPixelClock data even after the v40 ACPI fix (mutex chain works, but the
-	 * tables themselves return zero). Calling amdgpu_atombios_crtc_set_pll/
-	 * set_dtd_timing programs the hardware with garbage and breaks the BIOS-
-	 * default DP TX state that the MN864729 bridge needs to lock onto.
+	/* v45 (PS4 Liverpool/Gladius): v44 dump confirmed the kexec from PS4-OS
+	 * resets all four DCCG_PLL[0..3] banks to zero before our kernel runs.
+	 * ATOM AdjustDisplayPll/SetPixelClock can't help (PS4 VBIOS table data is
+	 * stub, returns 0 even with v40 ACPI fix). amdgpu must program the display
+	 * PLL itself by writing the divider registers directly.
 	 *
-	 * Strategy: skip all ATOM-driven mode_set work, preserve the PS4 boot
-	 * firmware's PLL/timing configuration, and only update what the framebuffer
-	 * scanout needs (those writes don't go through ATOM). Dump current PPLL state
-	 * to dmesg so we can see exactly what BIOS left us with. If the bridge still
-	 * doesn't get signal after this, the issue is upstream of the PLL (DP TX or
-	 * DIG encoder) and not anything mode_set can fix. */
+	 * Target: 1080p60 = 148.5 MHz pixel clock. Reference clock: 100 MHz (PCIE).
+	 * Standard avivo PLL math:
+	 *   pixel_clock = ref_clock * (fb_div_int + fb_div_frac/16) / ref_div / post_div
+	 * For 148.5 MHz: ref_div=1, fb_div_int=11, fb_div_frac=14, post_div=8
+	 *   → 100 * (11 + 14/16) / 1 / 8 = 148.4375 MHz (within HDMI ±0.5% tolerance)
+	 *   → VCO = 100 * 11.875 = 1187.5 MHz (within typical 600..1600 MHz range)
+	 *
+	 * Register layout from dce_8_0_sh_mask.h VGA*_PPLL_* (DCCG_PLL banks have
+	 * the same layout — both are CIK PPLL register banks):
+	 *   PLL_REF_DIV[9:0]  = ref_div
+	 *   PLL_FB_DIV[3:0]   = fb_div_frac (4-bit)
+	 *   PLL_FB_DIV[26:16] = fb_div_int (11-bit)
+	 *   PLL_POST_DIV[6:0] = post_div_pixclk (7-bit)
+	 *
+	 * Program ALL four PPLLs identically — whichever PPLL the PIXCLK_RESYNC
+	 * routes to our CRTC will then have valid dividers. This is overkill but
+	 * safe (other PPLLs aren't driving any active output yet).
+	 *
+	 * NOT doing in this iteration: PLL enable/reset/lock sequencing via
+	 * PLL_CNTL/PLL_UPDATE_LOCK. If the dividers alone don't unblock display,
+	 * v46 will layer on the enable sequence using radeon's CIK helper as
+	 * reference. */
 	if (adev->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL || adev->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS) {
-		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL0 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+		const u32 ref_div       = 1;
+		const u32 fb_div_int    = 11;
+		const u32 fb_div_frac   = 14;
+		const u32 post_div      = 8;
+
+		const u32 ref_div_val   = ref_div & 0x3ff;
+		const u32 fb_div_val    = (fb_div_frac & 0xf) | ((fb_div_int & 0x7ff) << 16);
+		const u32 post_div_val  = post_div & 0x7f;
+
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: v45 Liverpool PRE-program PPLL state:\n");
+		pr_info("  PPLL0: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_REF_DIV),
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_FB_DIV),
-			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_POST_DIV));
-		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL1 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_CNTL));
+		pr_info("  PPLL1: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_REF_DIV),
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_FB_DIV),
-			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_POST_DIV));
-		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL2 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_CNTL));
+		pr_info("  PPLL2: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_REF_DIV),
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_FB_DIV),
-			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_POST_DIV));
-		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL3 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_CNTL));
+		pr_info("  PPLL3: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_REF_DIV),
 			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_FB_DIV),
-			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_POST_DIV));
-		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PIXCLK0/1/2 RESYNC: 0x%08x 0x%08x 0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_CNTL));
+		pr_info("  PIXCLK0/1/2 RESYNC: 0x%08x 0x%08x 0x%08x  crtc_id=%d pll_id=%d\n",
 			RREG32(mmPIXCLK0_RESYNC_CNTL),
 			RREG32(mmPIXCLK1_RESYNC_CNTL),
-			RREG32(mmPIXCLK2_RESYNC_CNTL));
-		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool - preserving BIOS PLL/timing, "
-			"framebuffer-only setup (clock=%d kHz, x=%d, y=%d)\n",
-			adjusted_mode->clock, x, y);
+			RREG32(mmPIXCLK2_RESYNC_CNTL),
+			amdgpu_crtc->crtc_id, amdgpu_crtc->pll_id);
+		pr_info("  Target dividers: ref=%u fb_int=%u fb_frac=%u/16 post=%u → ~148.44 MHz\n",
+			ref_div, fb_div_int, fb_div_frac, post_div);
+		pr_info("  Packed values: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			ref_div_val, fb_div_val, post_div_val);
+
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_REF_DIV,  ref_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_FB_DIV,   fb_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_POST_DIV, post_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_REF_DIV,  ref_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_FB_DIV,   fb_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_POST_DIV, post_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_REF_DIV,  ref_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_FB_DIV,   fb_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_POST_DIV, post_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_REF_DIV,  ref_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_FB_DIV,   fb_div_val);
+		WREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_POST_DIV, post_div_val);
+
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: v45 Liverpool POST-program PPLL state:\n");
+		pr_info("  PPLL0: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_CNTL));
+		pr_info("  PPLL1: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_CNTL));
+		pr_info("  PPLL2: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_CNTL));
+		pr_info("  PPLL3: ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x cntl=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_POST_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_CNTL));

 		dce_v8_0_crtc_do_set_base(crtc, old_fb, x, y, 0);
 		dce_v8_0_cursor_reset(crtc);
